Monday #musings ✍🏼
People often misguidedly think that change only happens with big shifts-it doesn’t. 
Change happens incrementally- small, quiet baby steps of progression until one day we see how far we have come and how deep we have grown.
And with that an awakening and profound peace and deep compassion and tenderness for ourself. 
Allow life. 
Allow yourself to feel all you feel.
Meditation and deep inner soul work are essential to help us deal with all the things in life that we cannot control. 
Especially other humans.
We have to create a safe anchor and sacred sanctuary within ourselves. 
This is the one abiding constant that never changes, never wavers.
Everything else is constantly changing and out of control. 
We are not in the control seat of life as exasperating as that may feel. 
But we are in control of our thoughts. 
Meditate, learn to have some dominion over your mind-and then let go. 
Let go and give it over to God. 
Our life is a constant co-creation with the Divine. 
Do your part and trust in Spirit to do the rest. 
Life will never be easy. Accept that. 
Challenges are part and parcel of our human experience.
Meditation is the practice that helps us stay grounded amidst the inevitable turbulence and dualities of life. 
Do your best-lovingly, patiently, mercifully. Over and over. 
And then get on with the art and heart of living the extraordinary gift of life you’re blessed to still have. 
Until you don’t. 🖤✨🌟💫

Happy Monday all. 💗
Because I’m frequently asked-here are some tips on how I take care of my hair.

✨I wash my hair about every 4 or 5 days. Unless you have very fine hair too much shampooing can rob your hair of its natural oils.

✨ A day or 2 before I wash my hair I saturate the ends in an organic oil treatment and wear braids for a few days to let the oils penetrate my hair.

✨I use only #cleanbeauty #hairproducts that are sulfate, paraben, silicone free. YES to 💯 #biodegradable formulas, #vegan and #crueltyfree.

✨I rarely use very hot styling appliances( except on a professional shoot) as they damage hair especially fine, mature, silver and over chemically treated hair.

✨Before I wash my hair I use a scalp oil treatment because healthy hair starts with a healthy scalp.

✨After I wash my hair I generally let it air dry and then when it’s almost dry I gently twist it into a high chignon for about an hour and voila-soft #beachyhair without the damage.

✨I sleep on a silk pillow which is both excellent for hair and skin.

✨Treat your hair gently, use a soft towel to pat your hair dry and refrain from abrasive rubbing and pulling your hair.

✨The key to #beautifulhair at any age is to keep it trimmed, shiny and healthy. I find that soft layers around the face keep long hair looking fresh, modern and youthful. 

And that’s about it really. The less you do to your hair the better. I get gold blonde highlights every 2 months and I protect my hair from the sun and chlorine.

Yes, good genes help( my mum had a full head of thick hair into her 80’s) and clean living contributes to the health and condition of your locks.

And finally: ignore the memo that says older shouldn’t wear their hair long. Couldn’t be further from the truth. Make your own rules and #youdoyou 

Have a safe and healthy week ahead. 💗

Excerpt from my #nextbook ✍️

And how shall it end, this wild, precious life of mine-with a soft whimper and a gentle smile upon my face? 
With a heart full of love and a mind quietly at ease? 
A life fully lived and loved on my own recalcitrant terms? 
Yes, oh yes. 
Don’t we all hope for this? 
To not see our bodies shrivel away-nor lose our mind to the horrors of dementia. 
To not be a burden to those we love and leave behind. 
But I will take whatever life brings and handle it with as much resilience and courage as I can muster.
What more can any of us do? 
Our date with death will arrive, sometimes unannounced, sometimes expected, sometimes even welcomed when disease has ravaged the body and mind.
But along the way we let the mind have a field day. 
Ruminating, worrying, regretting.
Anything but accepting and allowing. 
Until it’s too late.
We think we have all the time in the world. 
We don’t.
We know this intrinsically, but most people live in denial. 
Daily focusing on my mortality is the fire that reminds me that each day could be my last.
Trivialities, moralizing and caution fly out the window as we lay down our armor and all that separates us from each other.
With more days behind me than in front it’s not about doing and having more.
It’s about treading lightly and finding something to celebrate everyday. 
Celebrate every tiny victory, every daily, hourly triumph. 
It’s about living the fruits of a deeply self-examined life. 
I shall be ready when death comes calling-in some distant future or even tomorrow. 
I shall be ready with no fret or mourning. 
I accept myself exactly as I am, with all my flawed humanity.
With great tenderness I carry within me the whole shimmering, complex, messy story of myself. 
Like a secret locket only I can see.
Lovely images I want to remember- painful memories I want to forget.
I choose not to live in the past, nor in despair over an unknown future. 
I pray that I may be free from pain, suffering and attachment at the end. 
That I may have a gentle passing.
Then another journey begins and a new adventure awaits. 
This little life-thank you for being mine, so beguilingly, unpredictably, beautifully mine. #mywords ❤️

It’s almost swimwear time (hopefully) and time to up your game/exercise routine.
My basic #workoutroutine is dance/Zumba 3 x a week. 
Upper body workout with weights 3x a week. 
Cardio on the in between days for about 30 mins.
Daily yoga stretches morning and evening. In the summer I like to hike and swim. 
And that’s about it. 
Do the work and get the results. 
Be the healthiest YOU can be, but don’t use age as an excuse. 
Most people can do some kind of workout even at home. Get a skip rope, buy some light weights, put on some music, watch an exercise video, walk/ hike , just #moveyourbody. 
And eat healthy for your body type. A nutritious diet, lots of water and regular exercise routine go together. 
I also practice #intermittentfasting so I eat most of my food between noon and 8pm. 
I’m a #pescatarian and enjoy sushi, a little pasta and chocolate. 
I enjoy a #vodkacocktail as vodka is the cleanest low calorie spirit and doesn’t leave a next day hangover. 
I don’t deny myself treats, but it takes discipline not to reach for late night snacks so I brush my teeth at around 8pm so I think twice about raiding the kitchen at 10pm. 
And personally I really don’t like waking up with a bloated stomach. I eat like this most of the time and especially if I have a #photoshoot or special event. 
But I don’t beat myself up if I cheat on occasion ( occasionally being the key word). There are 80 yr olds at my gym who constantly inspire and motivate me. We have this one precious body and it’s up to us to take excellent care of it. 
I have mild arthritis in my hands, toes and left hip, but I actually feel less pain when I’m moving my body. 
We don’t stop exercising because we get old- we get old because we stop exercising/dancing. 💃🏋️‍♂️🧘‍♀️🏊‍♀️

Sunday #musings ✍🏼☀️❤️💋

Every morning before I even open my eyes I say a silent prayer that goes like this: 

“Today Sunday 3/26/2023 will never come again and how I live these 24 hours is up to me. I do not have complete control over what shows up or is taken away, but I do have control over how I show up and respond to the fickle, unpredictable, ever-changing conditions of life.

I do not know how many years, months, weeks or even hours I have left in this life, but I set my intention today and always to live as fully, joyfully and attentively as I can.”

This longtime daily practice of naming the date along with my meditation practice helps ground me in the present moment. 
It reminds me that this is it, this irreplaceable day, this moment, this me, this Angela at this age will never be again.

Most of us do not know when our time is up and our days are numbered- but at my age -in my 60’s, I know I have less time ahead of me than behind me.

This knowing does not scare me, rather it is simply my blessed daily wake up call to continue to live a deep, rich, wild, free-spirited, risk-taking, brave & bold, heart-open life until my very last breath. 

Several times during the day I stop for a few minutes wherever I am, close my eyes, take some deep breaths and again remind myself to be awake to my thoughts, my emotions & the present moment. 

With age and a whisper of wisdom I’ve learned to tread lightly through my days as I have no time to waste racing through life on autopilot. 

Then at night after I close my eyes to sleep I always say a prayer of deep thankfulness for the gift of the day that I just had-no matter how it unfolded. And with it the sobering realization that I have one more day less to live.

This practice is the guiding anchor for how I live every single day. 

Reminding myself of my mortality has ironically become the path that has taught me how to live “my one precious life” with attentiveness, astonishment, wonder, curiosity and above all, abiding, profound gratitude. 

In the time I have left I ASPIRE to INSPIRE before I EXPIRE. ✨

There are so many people hurting and struggling in this mad, sad world full of turmoil, tragedy and upheaval. 

These past few years have affected us all to varying degrees and I hear so many people saying how hopeless they feel and are overwhelmed at just trying to make it through another day. 

Hope seems to be so hard to come by for so many. I no longer read the news, but it finds me. And every day there’s more strife, corruption, greed, injustice and chaos in the world. At times it’s hard to find the humane in humanity. 

I’m generally a naturally optimistic person. But as a sensitive empath sometimes I too have moments of overwhelm and deep sadness. So then I reach for the tools that help lift me up and remind me of the beauty and goodness in life and people.

Nature, Meditation and Poetry are where I always find poignant reassurance, calm, inspiration and yes, hope. 

This beautiful poem on HOPE has been a comfort to me and so with all the love, tenderness and compassion in my heart I share it with you and pray it can offer a grain of hope to you also. ✨💙✨

Poem by Denise Leverton

I have a small grain of hope- one crystal that gleams clear colors out of transparency.
I need more.
I break off a fragment to send you.
Please take this grain of a grain of hope so that mine won't shrink. 
Please share your fragment so that yours will grow.
Only so, by division will hope increase, like a clump of irises which will cease to flower unless you distribute the clustered roots, unlikely source-clumsy and earth covered- of grace. 💙

The beauty secret that serves women best is the knowledge that while superficial beauty may fade over time, beauty derived from wisdom, joy, experience, curiosity and joie de vivre does not.

Beauty as a commodity is bound to disappear with age. So if a woman’s self-worth is determined mostly by how she looks, then she will have a very difficult time when those looks inevitably, naturally fade. 

As a young model I learned early on that I would need a rich inner life, spiritual path, interests and passions to invest in the woman I wanted to become, and did.

It’s the light and glow in your smile and the intelligence, wit and mischief in your sparkling eyes.

It’s about the confidence that comes from a life fully lived and radiantly alive.
It’s about taking risks, reaching for your dreams and bravely living life on your terms at every chapter.

It’s the urgent understanding that there is literally no time or energy to waste on regrets or guilt. 

It’s being supremely at ease in your own skin and knowing and loving who you are in the deepest sense.

And it’s the profound knowing that life is incredibly fleeting and aging is indeed a privilege, not a punishment. 

We do not have endless tomorrows so live and love accordingly. ✨✍🏼✨

Wherever you are in the world I wish you all a safe and peaceful weekend. ☀️💛🌼

It’s just past noon and already I have so much to be thankful for.

I slept well and awoke in a clean comfortable bed. As always I took an invigorating cold shower and drank hot water, lemon and ginger.

I did my usual morning meditation/breathe work, had my coffee then I went to the gym and did a vigorous Zumba class that made me feel energized and radiantly alive.

Then I had the funds to go to the store and buy gorgeous flowers, healthy food and supplements to nourish this body. 

I did not have to get up early to go to a job I hate that pays little. 

Non of this I take for granted.

After these activities I said a silent prayer of gratitude for all my daily blessings. 

My family had very little money when I was a child so I know what it’s like to be poor and unable to afford groceries or even electricity.

I say my gratitude prayer throughout my day regardless of what is going on in my life. Gratitude is an active daily practice that can literally change our lives. 

Sometimes, like many people, I have had moments of great weariness and overwhelm during these past few years of global turmoil, upheaval and uncertainty.
I honor those feelings and let them have their moment. 

But they do not linger and live in my mind because I’m not attached to them.
I’m more focused on all the Grace, love and blessings that I have.

It’s about being awake to the multitude of blessings that we are all gifted with every single day. And it’s the awareness that times are hard for so many. 

People have lost income, health, jobs, loved ones and hope. #mentalillness is on the rise in all age groups. 

Too many are struggling to make ends meet & weighed down by debt and worries. Worry about how to take care of their families, and how to stay hopeful during these challenging times.

So, yes I count my blessings constantly and I feel rich beyond measure. 

From the moment I awake till the moment I close my eyes to sleep at night I give thanks for all that is, all that has been and all that is yet to be. 🙏✨🙏✨🙏✨🙏✨

A yoga teacher I admire recently posted that at one of her women’s retreats she asked all the women in the circle to share one thing or more that they thought was beautiful about their physical appearance. 

Sadly, she noted not one woman could muster words of self-love. So she started with herself and slowly & tentatively several women followed.

What happened in that yoga circle is a small example of how many women feel.
On one hand we exhort women to love themselves and claim their beauty-but when we do that very thing we’re often accused of being arrogant and vain. Or we’re accused of being “full of ourselves.” 

Personally I think we need a world of women full of themselves- full of self-love, self-worth, self-confidence and self-esteem.

But even more discouraging is that it is often women who are doing the judging of other women. 

Until we can see & celebrate our own beauty and light, how can we possibly see it in other’s? 

And what message does it send to our daughter’s and younger female friends. 
We need to encourage and lift each other up-not keep each other small & self-doubting. The world does enough of that already!

So it’s time to stand in front of the mirror and say out loud-or whisper it inwardly if you prefer.
I am gorgeous. 
Say it until you believe it. 
And be specific. Your mind and body will believe what you repeat. 

So I’ll start- I love my hair, legs, skin, smile and blue eyes that look like my mum’s.

I also love my wrinkles, my arthritic hands and feet, my round tummy, my wide nose, narrow shoulders, my caesarean scar and even my less than perky breasts. To be honest they look slightly more like milk jugs than champagne glass sized stunners.
But hey they’re real!!

Now your turn, all you beautiful goddess women out there-share & tell the world at least one thing you love about your physical beauty. ✨💛✨💛✨

Wednesday #musings ✍🏼 

I have a hope, a desire, a wish, should I be so blessed, to leave this earth with grace, with acceptance, with an open heart and peaceful mind. 

I hope to die without a list of regrets, risks not taken, dreams not fulfilled and love not expressed. And if I’m fortunate not too much physical suffering. 

How we live every single day will determine to a large degree how we experience not only our own death, but those of our loved ones as well. 

Are you living the life you really want? 
Are you courageously expressing your feelings and truth?
Are you caught up in the hustle and grind of work with little time for rest, pleasure, delight and magic? 

If we lived our lives with the awareness that there is no time to wait or waste, no endless supply of tomorrow’s-imagine how different life could change with this profound and powerful awareness.

This one life-transforming/ enhancing practice is the foundation that will serve you better than any 7 steps to happiness or 5 yr life plans. 

Personally I want to do all I can to prepare to experience a good death. 

A good death- yes I know to some it might sound like an oxymoron. Because that’s not how we’ve been taught to view life and death. We cheer and celebrate when a baby is born- and rightfully so, and then we weep and howl when death comes calling. 

In Eastern Spirituality death is also seen as a cause of celebration- a time of rebirth and a new journey and adventure where we simply let go of the physical shell that we inhabit for a short time.✨

Yes it might seem like one of those spiritual contradictions that may make your head spin, but peaceful open-hearted passings are possible by how we live our life now.

Here and now in this present fleeting moment. ✨

The beauty secret that serves women best is the knowledge that while superficial beauty may fade over time, beauty derived from wisdom, experience, curiosity and joie de vivre does not.

Beauty as a commodity is bound to disappear with age. So if a woman’s self-worth is determined mostly by how she looks, then she will have a very difficult time when those looks inevitably, naturally fade.

Confidence and self-respect is sexy and alluring-futile, desperate clinging to one’s youth is not.

As a young model I learned early on that I would need a rich inner life, a spiritual practice and passions to invest in to grow into the woman I wanted to become, and did.

It’s the light and glow in your smile and the intelligence, wit and mischief in your sparkling eyes.

It’s the maturity and soulfulness that comes from a life fully lived and feeling radiantly alive. 

It’s about the satisfaction and inner power that stems from taking risks, reaching for your dreams and bravely living life on your own terms at every chapter.

It’s the understanding that there is literally no time or energy to waste on regrets, shame or guilt.

It’s being supremely at ease in your own skin and knowing and loving who you are in the deepest sense.

And it’s the profound knowing that life is incredibly fleeting and aging is indeed a privilege-not a punishment as we’re falsely led to believe.

Obsessing and fretting over something we have no control over is a ridiculous waste of the precious time we have left.

We do not have endless tomorrows-so live, enjoy, celebrate and love accordingly.
